Thanks! Very much looking forward to seeing this definition in mathlib -- I need it to do the Tate curve in correct generality.
Thanks! Very much looking forward to seeing this definition in mathlib -- I need it to do the Tate curve in correct generality.
In this way `IsRankOne` is not a `Prop` right? I am not sure, but maybe we can redefine it asking the existence of `hom` (and then using choice to get one if we need).

Defining it as a `Prop` was my first approach, but I decided it against it because then I lose control of normalizations. In [this file](https://github.com/mariainesdff/norm_extensions_lean_4/blob/master/NormExtensions/NormedValued.lean), I define a dictionary between rank one valuations and nontrivial nonarchimedean norms, and I want to make sure that the normalized p-adic valuation corresponds to the normalized p-adic norm under this dictionary, but this isn't true if I can't control the inclusion of `WithZero (Multiplicative Z)` in `NNReal`. (I guess this may be possible renormalizing the map given by the existential, but I am not sure how the dictionary would have to be defined in that case, to work in general).
OK, if you have reasons to do it this way no problems. I am not sure about the name, even if we use `IsBlah` for non `Prop` in other places (but people regularly complain on Zulip).
Should I rename it to `RankOne`?
@kbuzzard what do you think? (Asking because you were involved in the Zulip discussion)

Yes I think `IsRankOne` is a recipe for confusion because people will assume it's a Prop. I don't think there are so many other places where we're using `Is` for a non-Prop: `IsROrC` got changed to `RCLike` for example.  Very happy with `RankOne`.

There should be a note in the docstring that this class contains the data of an injection of the target monoid into NNReal, so it's not a Prop.

If we want `IsRankOne`, it's just `Nonempty (RankOne)`.
I wasn't sure if `cases'` was still OK (I asked [here](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/287929-mathlib4/topic/Is.20cases'.20deprecated.3F/near/433616450), sorry to hold things up).
I can change it to cases.

Shouldn't this be `unit` because it's a term not a type? Similarly `Unit_le_one` below.

You could furthermore demand that the unit has norm strictly less than one, i.e. take the chance to normalise it now. You're already doing it nonconstructively. But probably you know more about why you want this than me.
So far, I just use this unit to show that `Γ₀ˣ` is nontrivial.

```suggestion
  refine (eq_of_le_of_not_lt (zero_le' (a := x)) fun h_lt ↦ ?_).symm
  have hs := strictMono v h_lt
  rw [_root_.map_zero, hx] at hs
  exact hs.false
```

```suggestion
  ⟨fun h ↦ zero_of_hom_zero v h, fun h ↦ by rw [h, _root_.map_zero]⟩
```
I think in Mathlib we agreed to use "↦" in place of "=>" in functions.

```suggestion
  Note that this class includes the data of an inclusion morphism `Γ₀ → ℝ≥0`. -/
```
